Captain Marvel is poised to be a big game-changer for Marvel Cinematic Universe (MCU) on multiple fronts, not just because it's the first female-led superhero film from Disney/Marvel Studios but also because it promises to have significant connections to Avengers: Endgame.

"I wanted to make a movie where [Captain Marvel] was not relegated to being just a superhero, or someone who only has value because of her physical strength," said Anna Boden co-director of the film along with Ryan Fleck at a press conference.
The movie follows a narrative where Danver's past and the circumstances leading to her transformation into Captain Marvel are revealed.
The movie is directed by Anna Boden (who directed Ryan Fleck) and scored a massive success at the box office, grossing over $1.1 billion worldwide.

The iconic character was first introduced in 1968 by Stan Lee and artist Gene Colan in Marvel Super-Heroes #13, Carol Danver became an empowered superhero due to exposure to radiation while encountering Captain Mar-Vell in issue #43 of Captain America vol.2 She later starred as the eponymous Ms Marvel since1977 before finally adopting her current name.
Captain Marvel has so far received a positive response from critics who have praised Larson's performance, visual effects, and its empowering message for young girls.

Captain Marvel arrives in theatres on International Women’s Day (March 8), offering an inspiring superheroine character that embodies both human and superhuman qualities - courage, strength, wit, and tenacity.
**When To Watch:** If you are looking for some intense action sequences, this is definitely worth checking out on opening night (or ASAP).
